<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12032c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12032c">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12032c"> 32(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Omar Homard Petris / Pince &mdash; Rire</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">En 1704, un Alg&eacute;rien fut instruit des v&eacute;rit&eacute;s chr&eacute;tiennes par Dom Hougats: &ldquo;Le 8 octobre 1704, dit un registre, Homar Mahomet, de Barbarie, fut baptis&eacute; par M. le chanoine Desnots; le dit <mark>Homard</mark> (sic) fut nomm&eacute; Nicolas Joseph <mark>P&eacute;tris</mark> et signa l&apos;acte de bapt&ecirc;me.&rdquo; <br>Pourquoi le nom d&apos;<mark>Omar</mark> fut-il transform&eacute; en celui de Homar et m&ecirc;me en Homard? Les bons scribes religieux pensaient-ils &agrave; ces excellents crustac&eacute;s, aux longues et fortes pinces, dont la baie de Saint-Malo &eacute;tait alors abondamment pourvue? C&apos;est une supposition; on comprend plus facilement qu&apos;Omar ait &eacute;t&eacute; pr&eacute;nomm&eacute; Nicolas, du nom de son parrain: mais pourquoi P&eacute;tris? Un savant &eacute;tymologiste auquel j&apos;ai confi&eacute; mon embarras, m&apos;a r&eacute;pondu: &ldquo;P&eacute;tris vient de petra, pierre; or le homard vit pr&eacute;cis&eacute;ment sous les pierres.&rdquo; Ce philologue me para&icirc;t, lui aussi, &ecirc;tre comme le homard: <mark>un pince sans rire</mark>. <br><font color="green">[In 1704, an Algerian was introduced into the christian truths by Dom Hougats: &ldquo;On 8 October 1704, says a register, Homar Mahomet, of Barbary, was baptized by M. the canon Desnots; this Homard (sic [the word means &lsquo;lobster&rsquo;]</font>) was given the name Nicolas Joseph P&eacute;tris and he signed the act of baptism.&rdquo; <br>Why was the name Omar changed into that of Homar and even of Homard? Were the good religious scribes thinking of the excellent crustaceans, with their sharp and long pincers, that live so abundantly in the bay of Saint-Malo? One can only suppose; we can easily see why Omar had Nicolas as a first name, the name of his sponsor: but why P&eacute;tris? An etymological expert with whom I shared my confusion, told me &ldquo;P&eacute;tris comes from petra, stone; the lobster lives underneath stones.&rdquo; This philologist seemed to me too a bit like a lobster: a dry wit <font color="green">[literally a pincer without laughter.]</font>] <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 156</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c12016f" href="c12all.htm#c12016f">VI.C.12:016(f)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
